<appendix id="quick_install">
  <title>Quick installation guide</title>
  <para>
    This appendix gives a brief overview how to install &ps4; on a
    cluster.  A detailed description can be found in <xref
    linkend="configuration"/> and <xref linkend="installation"/>.
  </para>
  <orderedlist>
    <listitem>
      <para><emphasis role="bold">Get the files</emphasis></para>
      <para>
        Get the required files from the <ulink
        url="http://www.parastation.com">&ps;
        homepage</ulink>. You may find various
        <!-- fg: TODO -->
        versions of &ps; and related software within the <ulink
        url="http://www.parastation.com/download.php">download
        section</ulink>. Remember: a license is necessary to run &ps;.
      </para>
<!--      
      <para>
	Depending on the Linux distribution in use the RPMs or the
	<filename>.tar.gz</filename> files are needed.
      </para>
-->
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para><emphasis role="bold">Shutdown</emphasis></para>
      <para>
	If this is actually not the first installation but an update of &ps;
	to a more up to date version first of all shut down the &ps; system.
	In order to do this startup <filename>psiadmin</filename> and do a
	<constant>shutdown</constant>.
      </para>
    </listitem>
    <listitem id="serverinstall">
      <para><emphasis role="bold">Install on the server</emphasis></para>
      <para>
	Install the &ps; distribution files on the server machine.
      </para>
      <para>
	If the <filename>.tar.gz</filename> files are used as installation
	source, <filename>PSM_INSTALL</filename> has to be executed manually.
      </para>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para><emphasis role="bold">Install on the nodes</emphasis></para>
      <para>
	Depending on the installation model (i.e. centralized or distributed),
	you have to execute <filename>PSM_INSTALL</filename> or to repeat step
	<xref linkend="serverinstall"/> on every node respectively.
      </para>
      <para>
        Beginning with version 4.1, the kernel modules will be
        installed in the
        directory<filename>/lib/modules/kernel/drivers/net/ps4</filename>.
        In order to do so, the modules installation utility
        <filename>psmodules_install</filename> should be used.
      </para>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para><emphasis role="bold">Configuration</emphasis></para>
      <para>
        Next the configuration file
        <filename>parastation.conf</filename>, normally located in
        <filename>/opt/parastation/config</filename>, has to be
        adapted to the local settings. A template file giving lots of
        hints could be found in
        <filename>/opt/parastation/config/parastation.conf.tmpl</filename>.
        The configuration could be verified using
        <!-- TODO: fg: reference -->
        <filename>/opt/parastation/bin/test_conf</filename>.
      </para>
      <para>
	If a centralized installation is used, this has to be done only on
	the server, otherwise this step has to be repeated on all nodes.
      </para>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para><emphasis role="bold">Startup &ps;</emphasis></para>
      <para>
	In order to startup the entire &ps; system, run
	<xref linkend="psiadmin"/> located in
	<filename>/opt/parastation/bin</filename> and execute
	<constant>add</constant>. This should bring up the &ps;
	daemon <xref linkend="psid"/> on every node. Alternatively you can
	start <xref linkend="psiadmin"/> with the <option>-s</option> option
	which does the add automatically.
      </para>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para><emphasis role="bold">Testing</emphasis></para>
      <para>
        A brief test of the whole communication and management system
        can be done using the <filename>test_nodes</filename> program.
        For a detailed description please refer to <xref
        linkend="testing"/> 
        <!-- TODO: fg: man page 
        or to the relevent manual page <xref
        linkend="test_pse"/> -->.
      </para>
    </listitem>
  </orderedlist>
</appendix>
